<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-05-30T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-05-30T10:00:00-05:00" n="145" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d145">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee/422:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-05-30T16:00:00+01:00">May 30,
                                    1933—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received May 30—12:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>673. Your 344, May 28, 11 p.m., is most satisfactory. We fully realize
                            the import of the considerations brought out in the last paragraph. The
                            aviation section of the British draft remains unchanged after the first
                            reading which was rather perfunctory except for the overwhelming demand
                            for eliminating the exception to bombing in outlying districts.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>